description:
In secure_zero(), the code casts a potentially misaligned pointer to unsigned long*:

```c
while (len > 0 && ((uintptr_t)p & (sizeof(unsigned long) - 1)) != 0) {
    *p++ = 0;
    len--;
}
/* Word-sized writes for the bulk (p is now word-aligned) */
while (len >= sizeof(unsigned long)) {
    *(volatile unsigned long *)p = 0;  // This cast
    p += sizeof(unsigned long);
    len -= sizeof(unsigned long);
}
```

The alignment loop above DOES align p to word boundary before the cast. The comment at line 61 is correct.

However, the cast discards the volatile qualifier temporarily. The pointer p is volatile uint8_t*, but we cast it to volatile unsigned long*. This is actually correct - we're preserving volatile.

Actually, looking more carefully - the alignment loop works correctly. After the first while loop, p IS aligned. The cast to (volatile unsigned long *)p is safe.

This is NOT a bug - the alignment handling is correct.
